🧠 What a “pattern library” really is

Think of your brain storing bundles, not individual moves:

stimulus → pattern ID → execution block

Instead of:
	•	“press this finger, then that one…”

You have:
	•	“Chord shape A”
	•	“Scale run B”
	•	“Transition C → D”

👉 One cue → whole sequence fires

⸻

⚡ Why it feels like speed dial

Because the system shifts from:

Search mode (slow)

What do I do next?
→ scan options
→ choose
→ act

to:

Lookup mode (fast)

Recognize pattern
→ retrieve
→ execute

No deliberation. Just index → run.

⸻

🎼 Real example (music)

You don’t read:
	•	note → translate → finger

You see:
	•	shape / interval / phrase

And your brain goes:

“oh, that pattern”
→ play entire chunk


⸻

🧩 Structure of a good pattern library

A strong one has 3 properties:

1. Chunked
	•	Stored as groups, not steps
	•	(phrases, combos, plays—not atoms)

2. Indexed by perception
	•	Triggered by:
	•	sight (note shape)
	•	feel (hand position)
	•	sound (interval)

👉 The cue matters more than the action

⸻

3. Linked (transitions matter)
	•	Not just patterns, but:

Pattern A → Pattern B → Pattern C

The transitions are where mastery lives.

⸻

